description:
Define the tagged memory protocol that replaces untyped PpuMemReq/PpuMemResp.

TYPES:

enum MemRegion { Vram, Oam }
enum MemClient { Cpu, BgFetcher, ObjFetcher, OamScanner, Dma }
enum PpuMemKind { Read, Write(uint<8>) }

struct MemTxnTag { region: MemRegion, client: MemClient, id: uint<4> }

enum PpuMemResult {
  Ok(uint<8>),
  Denied,
  UndefinedRead(VideoBlockReason),
}

enum VideoBlockReason {
  CpuBlockedByMode2,       -- OAM blocked during OAM scan
  CpuBlockedByMode3,       -- VRAM+OAM blocked during pixel transfer
  CpuBlockedByOamDma,      -- CPU blocked during DMA (except HRAM)
  PpuBlockedByOwnership,   -- PPU internal contention
}

struct PpuMemReq { tag: MemTxnTag, kind: PpuMemKind, addr: uint<16> }
struct PpuMemResp { tag: MemTxnTag, result: PpuMemResult }

struct PendingRead { tag: MemTxnTag, epoch: uint<4> }

PROTOCOL:
- PpuMemReq { tag, client, region, kind, addr } issued on dot N
- PpuMemResp { tag, outcome } arrives on dot N + L
- Responses matched architecturally by tag.id, NOT positionally
- Pending reads are explicit semantic state
- Blocked accesses return Denied / UndefinedRead, not fake stable data
- Both simulation and FPGA backends implement the SAME contract

The stable compare surface includes access outcomes and request/response pairing,
not just returned bytes. This is important for debugging (WHY was an access blocked?)
and for compare-policy control (exact $FF materialization is opt-in, not default).

WHY: Without request identity and pending-read matching, changes to adapters, RAM
inference, or fetch scheduling can silently change which response belongs to which
logical fetch. The epoch field on PendingRead prevents stale responses (from before
a window restart or fetch cancel) from mutating a fetcher that has moved on.

## Problem

The instruction LD SP, HL (opcode 0xF9) requires detecting the pattern:

    DecodedOp::Load$(
        dst8: Option::None,
        src8: Option::None,
        dst16: Option::Some(Operand16::RegisterPair$(pair: RegPair::SP)),
        src16: Option::Some(Operand16::RegisterPair$(pair: RegPair::HL)),
        addressing: AddressingMode::Register16,
    )

This exact deep match traversal appears in THREE separate functions in src/cpu/semantics.spade:

1. **direct_load_sp_write** (lines 957-1007, 50 lines)
   Checks if it's LD SP, HL and returns Option::Some(get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL)).
   The entire 50-line function exists just for this one instruction.

2. **direct_load_phase** (lines 1009-1059, 50 lines)
   Checks if it's LD SP, HL and returns Option::Some(Phase::Execute$(op: op)).
   Another 50 lines for the same single instruction.

3. **handle_execute Load arm** (lines 1933-2050, ~120 lines)
   Nested 10+ levels deep. The entire arm exists to handle the Execute phase of LD SP, HL (setting sp_write to HL's value). Every other branch returns the same fallback delta.

Total: ~220 lines across 3 functions for detecting and handling one instruction.

## Solution

### Step 1: Create a predicate

    fn is_ld_sp_hl(op: DecodedOp) -> bool {
        match op {
            DecodedOp::Load$(dst8, src8, dst16, src16, addressing) => {
                match (dst8, src8, dst16, src16, addressing) {
                    (Option::None, Option::None,
                     Option::Some(Operand16::RegisterPair$(pair: RegPair::SP)),
                     Option::Some(Operand16::RegisterPair$(pair: RegPair::HL)),
                     AddressingMode::Register16) => true,
                    _ => false,
                }
            },
            _ => false,
        }
    }

This is ~12 lines. (If Spade doesn't support nested tuple matching to this depth, use sequential guards.)

### Step 2: Replace the 3 functions

**direct_load_sp_write** becomes:

    fn direct_load_sp_write(op: DecodedOp, regs: Registers) -> Option<uint<16>> {
        if is_ld_sp_hl(op) { Option::Some(get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL)) } else { Option::None }
    }

**direct_load_phase** becomes:

    fn direct_load_phase(op: DecodedOp) -> Option<Phase> {
        if is_ld_sp_hl(op) { some_phase(Phase::Execute$(op: op)) } else { Option::None }
    }

**handle_execute Load arm** becomes:

    DecodedOp::Load$(dst8, src8, dst16, src16, addressing) => {
        let _ = (dst8, src8, dst16, src16, addressing);
        if is_ld_sp_hl(op) {
            CpuDelta$(
                regs_write: idle_reg_write_set(),
                pc_write: Option::None,
                sp_write: some_u16(get_r16(state.arch.regs, RegPair::HL)),
                ime_write: Option::None,
                halt_write: Option::None,
                micro_write: fetch_micro_write(),  // from bead bd-37qy
            )
        } else {
            fetch_only_delta()  // from bead bd-37qy
        }
    },

### Step 3: Also check control.spade loadish_fetch_phase

The Register16 arm (lines 105-129) and Immediate16 arm (lines 80-104) in loadish_fetch_phase also check for the SP/HL pattern. The is_ld_sp_hl predicate might help there too, but review carefully since those arms handle more cases.

## Files

- src/cpu/semantics.spade: direct_load_sp_write, direct_load_phase, handle_execute

## Dependencies

- Benefits from bd-37qy (fetch_only_delta / fetch_micro_write helpers)
- Benefits from bd-3i5p (tuple matching patterns)

## Estimated savings

~200 lines (220 lines of nesting -> ~20 lines with predicate + simplified functions)

## Verification

- All tests must pass.
- The LD SP,HL instruction is covered by cpu_instrs blargg tests. Run the full test suite.

Create src/bus/types.spade with all bus interface types from §12.2.

CPU-facing bus contract (minimal, §12.2):
  enum BusReq { Idle, Read{addr: uint<16>}, Write{addr: uint<16>, data: uint<8>} }
  struct BusResp { data: uint<8> }

Simulation-only observation sideband (§12.2.1):
  enum BusRegion { Rom, Vram, CartRam, Wram, Echo, Oam, NotUsable, Io, Hram, Ie }
  struct BusObs { region: BusRegion, blocked: bool, owner: BusOwner }

Bus ownership (§12.2.2):
  enum BusOwner { Cpu, OamDma, Ppu, Idle }

DESIGN PRINCIPLES:
- CPU always emits plain BusReq. DMA/PPU contention resolved in fabric, NOT in CPU (§12.2.2)
- BusObs is for commit traces and diagnostics only. Do NOT widen CPU bus contract until concrete need (§12.2.1)
- Keep it simple initially. Add complexity only when Wave C (DMA/MBC) requires it
- BusReq::Idle ensures quiescent buses when no access needed (§18.3 power)

Create src/cpu/types.spade with all core CPU types from §7.2 and §8.1-8.2.

═══ ARCHITECTURAL STATE (§7.1A) ═══
  enum ImeState { Disabled, PendingEnable, Enabled }
  enum HaltState { Running, Halted, HaltBugPending }
  struct CpuArchState { regs: Registers, ime_state: ImeState, halt_state: HaltState }

═══ MICROSTATE (§7.1B) ═══
  struct CpuMicroState { phase: Phase, opcode_latch: uint<8>, imm_lo: uint<8>, imm_hi: uint<8>, decoded: DecodedOp, temp: uint<16> }
  struct CpuState { arch: CpuArchState, micro: CpuMicroState }

═══ PHASE ENUM (§8.1) — TYPE SYSTEM MAKES ILLEGAL COMBINATIONS IMPOSSIBLE ═══
  enum PrefixKind { Cb }
  enum Phase {
    Fetch,
    FetchPrefix { prefix: PrefixKind },
    ReadImm8 { k: Imm8Cont },
    ReadImm16Lo { k: Imm16Cont },
    ReadImm16Hi { lo: uint<8>, k: Imm16HiCont },
    ReadMem { addr: uint<16>, k: ReadCont },
    WriteMem { addr: uint<16>, data: uint<8>, k: WriteCont },
    Execute { op: DecodedOp },
    ServiceInterrupt { irq: IrqSel, subphase: IrqPhase },
    Halted,
  }

═══ CONTINUATION ENUMS (§8.2) — CARRY SEMANTIC INTENT IN THE TYPE ═══
  enum ReadCont { LoadReg8{dst: R8}, LoadAFromAddr, AluFromMem{kind: AluKind}, PopLo{pair: RegPair}, PopHi{pair: RegPair, lo: uint<8>} }
  enum WriteCont { StoreDone, PushHi{next_pc: uint<16>}, PushLo{low: uint<8>, target: uint<16>} }
  (Imm8Cont, Imm16Cont, Imm16HiCont should follow the same typed-continuation pattern)

═══ INTERRUPT TYPES (for ServiceInterrupt phase variant) ═══
  enum IrqSel { VBlank, LcdStat, Timer, Serial, Joypad }
  enum IrqPhase { Delay1, Delay2, PushPcHi, PushPcLo, Jump }
  struct IrqPending { pending: uint<5> }  // = IE & IF, computed in peripheral layer
  struct IrqAck { ack_bit: Option<uint<3>> }  // which interrupt CPU is acknowledging

═══ MICRO INPUT/OUTPUT (§7.2) ═══
  struct MicroInput { bus_resp: BusResp, irq_pending: IrqPending }
  struct MicroOutput { delta: CpuDelta, bus_req: BusReq, commit: Option<CommitTrace>, sideband: Option<Sideband> }

═══ SPARSE DELTA TYPE (§7.2, §18.4 — CRITICAL FOR POWER) ═══
  struct RegWriteSet { a: Option<uint<8>>, f: Option<uint<8>>, b: Option<uint<8>>, ... }
  struct MicroWriteSet { phase: Option<Phase>, opcode_latch: Option<uint<8>>, ... }
  struct CpuDelta { regs_write: RegWriteSet, pc_write: Option<uint<16>>, sp_write: Option<uint<16>>, ime_write: Option<ImeState>, halt_write: Option<HaltState>, micro_write: MicroWriteSet }

  WHY SPARSE DELTAS: §18.4 requires that each register has its own write-enable. CpuDelta returns only the fields that change. apply_delta merges them into the current state. This prevents "update the whole state bundle just because one field changes" — both a correctness discipline and a power architecture requirement.

═══ SEMANTIC STEP INTERFACE (§7.2 — THE HEART OF THE PROJECT) ═══
  fn step_mcycle(state: CpuState, input: MicroInput) -> MicroOutput
  fn apply_delta(state: CpuState, delta: CpuDelta) -> CpuState

  step_mcycle is the DENOTATION of one machine step. apply_delta is the pure reconstruction used by tests and reference models. The cpu_core entity evaluates step_mcycle combinationally and commits its delta on m_ce.

DESIGN NOTES:
- The exact spellings may evolve during implementation. What matters is: typed continuations, sparse deltas, three-layer state split.
- HaltBugPending is designed in now but can be a stub until the interrupt milestone (§8.3).
- IrqSel/IrqPhase are needed for the Phase::ServiceInterrupt variant. They must be defined here even though interrupt implementation comes in Phase 4.
- All Option types represent "no change" / "no action" — they are the core mechanism for write-enable minimization.

Define the core PPU state model in src/ppu/sem/types.spade.

This file establishes the fundamental architectural vocabulary. Every other PPU
file depends on these types.

TYPES TO DEFINE:

struct PpuRegs {
  lcdc: Lcdc, stat_sel: StatSelect, scy: uint<8>, scx: uint<8>,
  lyc: uint<8>, wy: uint<8>, wx: uint<8>, bgp: uint<8>,
  obp0: uint<8>, obp1: uint<8>,
}

struct Lcdc {
  lcd_enable, win_map_hi, win_enable, bgwin_data_hi, bg_map_hi,
  obj_size_8x16, obj_enable, bg_enable: bool
}

struct StatSelect { lyc_sel, mode2_sel, mode1_sel, mode0_sel: bool }

struct PpuVisibleState { regs: PpuRegs, ly: uint<8> }
  NOTE: NO mode field, NO lcd_enabled field. These are DERIVED.

struct PpuStatusState { run: LcdRunState, stat_irq: StatIrqState }

enum LcdRunState { Disabled, WarmupBlankFrame, Running }
struct StatIrqState { line_high: bool }

enum PpuPhase {
  LcdOff,
  OamScan { index: uint<6>, found: uint<4> },
  Transfer { x_out: uint<8>, discard_scx: uint<3>, ... },
  HBlank { dots_left: uint<9> },
  VBlank { line: uint<8>, dots_left: uint<9> },
}

enum WindowState { Inactive, ArmedThisFrame, ActiveOnLine { win_x: uint<5>, win_line: uint<8> } }

struct PpuRenderState {
  dot_in_line: uint<9>, x_out: uint<8>, window_state: WindowState,
  window_line: uint<8>, oam_scan: OamScanState, line_objs: LineObjList,
  fetcher: FetcherState, bg_fifo: BgFifo, obj_fifo: ObjFifo,
  first_frame_blank: bool,
}

struct PpuState { visible: PpuVisibleState, status: PpuStatusState,
                  sampled: PpuSamplingState, render: PpuRenderState }

DERIVED PROJECTION FUNCTIONS:
  fn visible_mode(status: PpuStatusState) -> PpuMode
  fn lcd_enabled(status: PpuStatusState, regs: PpuRegs) -> bool

WHY: Storing mode and lcd_enabled independently creates impossible states like
mode=PixelTransfer while lcd_enabled=false. Deriving them from LcdRunState+PpuPhase
makes the type system enforce valid combinations. Pan Docs says STAT mode bits
report 0 when PPU is disabled -- that is naturally expressed as a projection from
LcdRunState::Disabled, not as a stored field that must be kept in sync.

Define the pixel pipeline output types and three-stage object representation.

SCANOUT CONTRACT:

struct PixelEmit { x: uint<8>, y: uint<8>, shade: uint<2>, source: PixelSource }

enum BlankReason {
  LcdDisabled,       -- LCDC.7 off, screen immediately blank
  WarmupBlankFrame,  -- first frame after LCD re-enable
  NonVisibleLine,    -- VBlank lines 144-153
  NonVisibleDot,     -- HBlank dots
}

enum ScanoutEvent {
  Pixel(PixelEmit),
  Blank { y: uint<8>, reason: BlankReason },
  FrameStart,
  LineStart { y: uint<8> },
}

WHY ScanoutEvent instead of Option<PixelEmit>: The old design left too much
implicit around LCD-off, warmup blanking, and non-visible scanout. Pan Docs says
disabling LCD blanks immediately; PyBoy returns (0,0,0,0) when LCD is off. An
explicit scanout contract prevents sinks from inferring blank conditions from side
state and makes the boundary reusable for future display adapters.

THREE-STAGE OBJECT PIPELINE:

struct SelectedObjTicket {
  oam_index: uint<6>, x: uint<8>, y: uint<8>, selection_rank: uint<4>
}

struct ResolvedObjMeta {
  ticket: SelectedObjTicket, tile: uint<8>, flags: ObjFlags, row_index: uint<4>
}

struct ObjPixel {
  color: uint<2>, palette: ObjPaletteSel, draw_rank: ObjDrawRank, bg_over_obj: bool
}

WHY THREE STAGES: Pan Docs distinguishes selection (Y overlap, OAM order) from
draw priority (smaller X, then earlier OAM). Splitting into ticket/metadata/pixel
keeps DMA corruption and metadata-race tests local to the fetch path (stage 2)
without contaminating selection semantics (stage 1).

## Problem

In src/cpu/control.spade, the function loadish_fetch_phase has two match arms that are 100% identical code:

- AddressingMode::MemoryViaHlIncrement (lines 186-211, 25 lines)
- AddressingMode::MemoryViaHlDecrement (lines 212-237, 25 lines)

Both arms contain the exact same nested match structure:

    match dst8 {
        Option::Some(dst8_value) => {
            match src8 {
                Option::Some(src8_value) => {
                    match dst8_value {
                        Operand8::Register$(r8) => {
                            let _ = src8_value;
                            Phase::ReadMem$(addr: get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL), k: ReadCont::LoadReg8$(dst: r8))
                        },
                        _ => {
                            match src8_value {
                                Operand8::Register$(r8) => {
                                    Phase::WriteMem$(addr: get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL), data: get_r8(regs, r8), k: WriteCont::StoreDone)
                                },
                                _ => Phase::Fetch,
                            }
                        },
                    }
                },
                Option::None => Phase::Fetch,
            }
        },
        Option::None => Phase::Fetch,
    }

The HL post-increment/decrement adjustment is handled separately in hl_post_adjust (lines 28-36) and load_hl_adjust in semantics.spade, NOT in control.spade. So these two arms are truly identical here.

## Solution

### Option A: Extract a helper function

    fn hl_indirect_load_store_phase(
        regs: Registers,
        dst8: Option<Operand8>,
        src8: Option<Operand8>,
    ) -> Phase {
        match (dst8, src8) {
            (Option::Some(Operand8::Register$(r8)), Option::Some(_)) =>
                Phase::ReadMem$(addr: get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL), k: ReadCont::LoadReg8$(dst: r8)),
            (_, Option::Some(Operand8::Register$(r8))) =>
                Phase::WriteMem$(addr: get_r16(regs, RegPair::HL), data: get_r8(regs, r8), k: WriteCont::StoreDone),
            _ => Phase::Fetch,
        }
    }

Then both arms and also AddressingMode::MemoryViaHl (lines 130-159) which has the same structure can all call this helper. That would eliminate ~75 lines (3 arms x 25 lines -> 3 x 1 line + 10 line helper).

### Option B: If Spade supports or-patterns

    AddressingMode::MemoryViaHlIncrement | AddressingMode::MemoryViaHlDecrement => {
        // single body
    }

Check if Spade supports this syntax. If not, use Option A.

## Files

- src/cpu/control.spade: loadish_fetch_phase function

## Estimated savings

~50 lines (25 duplicated + shared helper also absorbs MemoryViaHl arm).

## Verification

- All tests must pass.
- Confirm synthesis equivalence via Verilog diff.
